    <h1 class="text-center">Unveiling SpiceRAT: SneakyChef&#x27;s latest tool targeting EMEA and Asia</h1>

    <div class="text-center m-1">
        <div class="post-author">
            <span>By </span>
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/chetan/">Chetan Raghuprasad</a>, 
                <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/author/ashley/">Ashley Shen</a>
        </div>

        <br/>
        <time class="post-datetime" datetime="June 21, 2024 08:00">
            Friday, June 21, 2024 08:00
        </time>

        <div class="m-3">
                            <a href="/category/threats/" class="category primary-category">
                                Threats
                            </a>
                                                    <a href="/category/rat/" class="category primary-category">
                                RAT
                            </a>
                                </div>
    </div>

    <section class="post-content-wrapper mt-5">
        <div class="post-content">
            <ul><li>Cisco Talos discovered a new remote access trojan (RAT) dubbed SpiceRAT, used by the threat actor <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/sneakychef-sugarghost-rat/" rel="noreferrer"><u>SneakyChef</u></a> in a recent campaign targeting government agencies in EMEA and Asia.&nbsp;</li><li>We observed that SneakyChef launched a phishing campaign, sending emails delivering SugarGh0st and SpiceRAT with the same email address.&nbsp;</li><li>We identified two infection chains used to deliver SpiceRAT utilizing LNK and HTA files as the initial attack vectors.&nbsp;</li></ul><p><em>Cisco Talos would like to thank the Yahoo! Paranoids Advanced Cyber Threats Team for their collaboration in this investigation.</em>&nbsp;</p><h1 id="sneakychef-delivered-spicerat-to-target-angola-government-with-lures-from-turkmenistan-news-agency">SneakyChef delivered SpiceRAT to target Angola government with lures from Turkmenistan news agency&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos recently revealed <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/sneakychef-sugarghost-rat/" rel="noreferrer"><u>SneakyChef’s</u></a> continuing campaign targeting government agencies across several countries in EMEA and Asia, delivering the SugarGh0st malware (read the corresponding research <a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/sneakychef-sugarghost-rat/" rel="noreferrer"><u>here</u></a>). However, we found a new malware we dubbed “SpiceRAT” was also delivered in this campaign.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>SneakyChef is using a name "ala de Emissão do Edifício B Mutamba" and the email address “dtti.edb@[redated]” to send several phishing emails with at least 28 different RAR file attachments to deliver either SugarGh0st or SpiceRAT.&nbsp;</p><p>One of the decoy PDFs that we analysed in this campaign was dropped by a RAR archive, delivered as an attachment in the emails likely targeted Angolan government agencies. The decoy PDF contained lures from the Turkmenistan state-owned news media “ТУРКМЕНСКАЯ ГОСУДАРСТВЕННАЯ ИЗДАТЕЛЬСКАЯ СЛУЖБА” (Neytralnyy Turkmenistan), indicating that the actor has likely downloaded the PDF from their official <a href="https://metbugat.gov.tm/ru/newspaper/2?page=1" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>website</u></a>. We also found that a similar decoy PDF from the same news agency was dropped by the RAR archive that delivered the SugarGh0st malware in this campaign, highlighting that SneakyChef has SugarGh0st RAT and SpiceRAT payloads in their arsenal.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-73390e1a-6e63-440b-a58e-3823734a38d2.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1039" height="751" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-73390e1a-6e63-440b-a58e-3823734a38d2.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-73390e1a-6e63-440b-a58e-3823734a38d2.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-73390e1a-6e63-440b-a58e-3823734a38d2.png 1039w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Decoy PDF samples of SugarGh0st and SpiceRAT attacks.</em></i></figcaption></figure><h1 id="two-infection-chains">Two infection chains&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos discovered two infection chains employed by SneakyChef to deploy SpiceRAT. Both infection chains involved multiple stages launched by an HTA or LNK file.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><h2 id="lnk-based-infection-chain">LNK-based infection chain&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-c4c23a11-6401-4c3b-a934-c96ba8b672be.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="1401" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-c4c23a11-6401-4c3b-a934-c96ba8b672be.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-c4c23a11-6401-4c3b-a934-c96ba8b672be.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-c4c23a11-6401-4c3b-a934-c96ba8b672be.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The LNK-based infection chain begins with a malicious RAR file that contains a Windows shortcut file (LNK) and a hidden folder. This folder contains multiple components, including a malicious executable launcher, a legitimate executable, a malicious DLL loader, an encrypted SpiceRAT masquerading as a legitimate help file (.HLP) and a decoy PDF. The table below shows an example of the components of this attack chain and the description.&nbsp;</p>

<p>When the victim extracts the RAR file, it drops the LNK and a hidden folder on their machine. After a victim opens the shortcut file, which masqueraded as a PDF document, it executes an embedded command to run the malicious launcher executable from the dropped hidden folder.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-cedd5cae-cdb4-48b7-acd8-470b89c7fb38.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="961" height="763" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-cedd5cae-cdb4-48b7-acd8-470b89c7fb38.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-cedd5cae-cdb4-48b7-acd8-470b89c7fb38.png 961w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sample LNK file that starts the malicious launcher EXE.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>This malicious launcher executable is a 32-bit binary compiled on Jan. 2, 2024. infection, which will sideload the malicious DLL loader to decrypt and launch the SpiceRAT payload.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><h2 id="hta-based-infection-chain">HTA-based infection chain&nbsp;</h2><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-092e5a80-3575-4232-9656-7bd87dbeb3ce.jpeg" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1416" height="1600" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-092e5a80-3575-4232-9656-7bd87dbeb3ce.jpeg 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-092e5a80-3575-4232-9656-7bd87dbeb3ce.jpeg 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-092e5a80-3575-4232-9656-7bd87dbeb3ce.jpeg 1416w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The HTA-based infection chain also begins with a RAR archive delivered with the email. The RAR file contains a malicious HTA file. When the victim runs the malicious HTA file, the embedded malicious Visual Basic script executes and drops the embedded base64-encoded downloader binary into the victim’s user profile temporary folder, disguised as a text file named “Microsoft.txt.”&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-3f582708-1f05-4589-b702-67f1b2fc0842.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="383" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-3f582708-1f05-4589-b702-67f1b2fc0842.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-3f582708-1f05-4589-b702-67f1b2fc0842.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-3f582708-1f05-4589-b702-67f1b2fc0842.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>After dropping the malicious downloader executable, the HTA file executes another function, which drops and executes a Windows batch file in the victim’s user profile temporary folder, named “Microsoft.bat.”&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-0a61d476-4c3e-4a4c-b3cc-e3e427bb5e00.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="454" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-0a61d476-4c3e-4a4c-b3cc-e3e427bb5e00.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-0a61d476-4c3e-4a4c-b3cc-e3e427bb5e00.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-0a61d476-4c3e-4a4c-b3cc-e3e427bb5e00.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The malicious batch file performs the following operations on the victim’s machine:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>The <code>certutil</code> command decodes the base64-encoded binary data from “Microsoft.txt” and saves it as “Microsoft.exe” in the victim’s user profile temporary folder. &nbsp;</li></ul>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<table style="border: medium; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; width: 468pt;"><colgroup><col></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 0pt;"><td style="border-width: 1pt; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: top; padding: 5pt; overflow: hidden; overflow-wrap: break-word;"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">certutil -decode %temp%\\Microsoft.txt %temp%\\Microsoft.exe</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<ul><li>It creates a Windows scheduled task that runs the malicious downloader every five minutes, supressing any warnings that it triggers when the same task name existed.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<table style="border: medium; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; width: 650pt;"><colgroup><col></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 0pt;"><td style="border-width: 1pt; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: top; padding: 5pt; overflow: hidden; overflow-wrap: break-word;"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">schtasks /create /tn MicrosoftEdgeUpdateTaskMachineClSAN /tr %temp%\\Microsoft.exe /sc minute -mo 5 /F&nbsp;</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<ul><li>The batch script creates another Windows task named “MicrosoftDeviceSync” to run a downloaded legitimate executable “ChromeDriver.exe” every 10 minutes.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<table style="border: medium; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; width: 650pt;"><colgroup><col></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 0pt;"><td style="border-width: 1pt; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: top; padding: 5pt; overflow: hidden; overflow-wrap: break-word;"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;  font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">schtasks /create /tn MicrosoftDeviceSync /tr C:\\ProgramData\\Chrome\\ChromeDirver.exe /sc minute -mo 10 /F&nbsp;</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<ul><li>After establishing persistence with the Windows scheduled task, the batch script runs three other commands to erase the infection markers. This includes deleting the Windows task named <code>MicrosoftDefenderUpdateTaskMachineClSAN</code> and removing the encoded downloader “Microsoft.txt,” the malicious HTA file, and any other contents unpacked from the RAR file attachment.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li></ul>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<table style="border: medium; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; width: 468pt;"><colgroup><col></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 0pt;"><td style="border-width: 1pt; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: top; padding: 5pt; overflow: hidden; overflow-wrap: break-word;"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;  font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">schtasks /delete /f /tn MicrosoftDefenderUpdateTaskMachineClSAN&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color:  font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">del /f /q %temp%\\Microsoft.txt %temp%\\Microsoft.hta&nbsp;</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;  font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">del %0&nbsp;</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<p>The malicious downloader is a 32-bit executable compiled on March 5, 2024. After running on the victim’s machine through the Windows task <code>MicrosoftEdgeUpdateTaskMachineClSAN</code>, it downloads a malicious archive file “chromeupdate.zip” from an attacker-controlled server through a hardcoded URL and unpacks its contents into the folder at “C:\ProgramData\Chrome”. The unpacked files are the components of SpiceRAT.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5de50057-35f8-4f90-86c3-c38c0f116d82.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1554" height="1000" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-5de50057-35f8-4f90-86c3-c38c0f116d82.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-5de50057-35f8-4f90-86c3-c38c0f116d82.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5de50057-35f8-4f90-86c3-c38c0f116d82.png 1554w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function of the malicious downloader.</em></i></figcaption></figure><h1 id="analysis-of-spicerat">Analysis of SpiceRAT&nbsp;</h1><p>Both infection chains eventually drop the SpiceRAT files into victim machines. The SpiceRAT files include four main components: a legitimate executable file, a malicious DLL loader, an encrypted payload and the downloaded plugins.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><h2 id="the-loader-components-of-spicerat">The loader components of SpiceRAT&nbsp;</h2><h3 id="legitimate-executable">Legitimate executable&nbsp;</h3><p>The threat actor is using a legitimate executable (named “RunHelp.exe”) as a launcher to sideload the malicious DLL loader file (ssMUIDLL.dll). This legitimate executable is a Samsung RunHelp application signed with the certificate of "Samsung Electronics CO., LTD.” In some instances, it has been observed masquerading as “dxcap.exe,” a DirectX diagnostic included with Visual Studio, and “ChromeDriver.exe,” an executable that Selenium WebDriver uses to control the Google Chrome web browser.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-3c807403-8ebf-42f2-8c4e-51143d0bf630.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="821" height="285" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-3c807403-8ebf-42f2-8c4e-51143d0bf630.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-3c807403-8ebf-42f2-8c4e-51143d0bf630.png 821w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">File properties and digital signature details of the legitimate executable.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>The legitimate Samsung helper application typically loads a DLL called “ssMUIDLL.dll.” In this attack, the threat actor abuses the application by sideloading a malicious DLL loader that is masquerading as the legitimate DLL and executes its exported function <code>GetFulllangFileNamew2</code>.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-9b65b9b4-726d-4843-8211-46480faf2a1e.png" class="kg-image" alt="A screen shot of a computer program

Description automatically generated" loading="lazy" width="728" height="500" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-9b65b9b4-726d-4843-8211-46480faf2a1e.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-9b65b9b4-726d-4843-8211-46480faf2a1e.png 728w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Sample function that side-loads the malicious DLL.</em></i></figcaption></figure><h3 id="malicious-dll-loader">Malicious DLL loader&nbsp;</h3><p>The malicious loader is a 32-bit DLL compiled on Jan. 2, 2024. When its exported function GetFullLangFileNameW2() is run, it copies the downloaded legitimate executable into the folder "C:\Users\&lt;user&gt;\AppData\Local\data\” as “dxcap.exe” along with the malicious DLL “ssMUIDLL.dll” and the encrypted SpiceRAT payload “CGMIMP32.HLP.” &nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-ccaae504-86d1-4b14-8914-e05631b467ef.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="881" height="707" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-ccaae504-86d1-4b14-8914-e05631b467ef.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-ccaae504-86d1-4b14-8914-e05631b467ef.png 881w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function copies the SpiceRAT components.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>It executes the <code>schtasks</code> command to create a Windows task named “Microsoft Update,” configured to run “dxcap.exe” every two minutes. This technique establishes persistence at multiple locations on the victim's machine to maintain resilience.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!--kg-card-begin: html-->
<table style="border: medium; border-collapse: collapse; table-layout: fixed; width: 650pt;"><colgroup><col></colgroup><tbody><tr style="height: 0pt;"><td style="border-width: 1pt; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); vertical-align: top; padding: 5pt; overflow: hidden; overflow-wrap: break-word;"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 12pt; margin-bottom: 12pt;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;  font-weight: 700; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-variant-alternates: normal; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; font-variant-position: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;">schtasks&nbsp; -CreAte -sC minute -mo 2 -tn "Microsoft Update" -tr "C:\Users\&lt;User&gt;\AppData\Local\data\dxcap.exe"&nbsp;</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--kg-card-end: html-->
<figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-309b6f61-0441-4317-aa3d-0f34e24cc323.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="881" height="754" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-309b6f61-0441-4317-aa3d-0f34e24cc323.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-309b6f61-0441-4317-aa3d-0f34e24cc323.png 881w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function that creates Windows task.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>Then the loader DLL takes the snapshot of the running processes in the victim machine and checks if the legitimate executable that sideloads this malicious DLL is being debugged by querying its process information using “NtQueryInformationProcess.”&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-e69f48b5-a342-4e9c-bcfd-07e8f035ba99.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1135" height="292" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-e69f48b5-a342-4e9c-bcfd-07e8f035ba99.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-e69f48b5-a342-4e9c-bcfd-07e8f035ba99.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-e69f48b5-a342-4e9c-bcfd-07e8f035ba99.png 1135w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>The loader DLL executes another function that loads the encrypted file “CGMIMP32.HLP,” which is masquerading as a legitimate Windows help file into memory and decrypts it using the RC4 encryption algorithm. In one of the samples, we found that the DLL used a key phrase “{11AADC32-A303-41DC-BF82-A28332F36A2E}” for decrypting SpiceRAT in memory. After decryption, the loader DLL injects and runs the SpiceRAT from memory to its parent process “dxcap.exe.”&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-6b22e28c-2518-4078-a1c7-34197de022b7.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1374" height="667" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-6b22e28c-2518-4078-a1c7-34197de022b7.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-6b22e28c-2518-4078-a1c7-34197de022b7.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-6b22e28c-2518-4078-a1c7-34197de022b7.png 1374w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function that decrypts the SpiceRAT in memory.</em></i></figcaption></figure><h2 id="the-spicerat-payloads">The SpiceRAT payloads&nbsp;</h2><p>Talos discovered that SneakyChef has employed SpiceRAT and its plugin as the payloads in this campaign. With the capability to download and run executable binaries and arbitrary commands, SpiceRAT significantly increases the attack surface on the victim’s network, paving the way for further attacks.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>SpiceRAT is a 32-bit Windows executable with three malicious export functions <code>GetFullLangFileNameW2</code>, <code>WinHttpPostShare</code> and <code>WinHttpFreeShareFree</code>. Initially, it executes the <code>GetFullLangFileNameW2</code> function, creating a mutex as an infection marker on the victim machine. The mutex name is hardcoded in the RAT binary. We spotted two different mutex names among the SpiceRAT samples that we analyzed:&nbsp;</p><ul><li>{00866F68-6C46-4ABD-A8D6-2246FE482F99}&nbsp;&nbsp;</li><li>{00861111-3333-4ABD-GGGG-2246FE482F99}&nbsp;</li></ul><p>After the Mutex is created, the RAT collects reconnaissance data from the victim’s machine, including the operating system’s version number, hostname, username, IP address and the system’s network card hardware address (MAC address). The reconnaissance data is then encrypted and stored in the machine’s memory.&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-b6e03ee2-e186-4692-899d-23f8b29d7cbf.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="588" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-b6e03ee2-e186-4692-899d-23f8b29d7cbf.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-b6e03ee2-e186-4692-899d-23f8b29d7cbf.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-b6e03ee2-e186-4692-899d-23f8b29d7cbf.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function that encrypts the reconnaissance data in memory.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>During runtime, the RAT loads the WININET.dll file and imports the addresses of its functions to prepare for C2 communication.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-81af3685-07b1-47f1-8ffc-167aa0ec0180.png" class="kg-image" alt="A screen shot of a computer program

Description automatically generated" loading="lazy" width="616" height="554" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-81af3685-07b1-47f1-8ffc-167aa0ec0180.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-81af3685-07b1-47f1-8ffc-167aa0ec0180.png 616w"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function that loads the APIs of WININET.dll.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>Once the function addresses of WININET.dll are imported, the RAT executes the <code>WinHttpPostShare</code> function to communicate with the C2. It connects to the C2 server with a hardcoded URL in the binary and through the HTTP POST method.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Then, it attempts to read and send the encrypted stream of reconnaissance data and user credentials from memory to the C2 server. The C2 server responds with an encrypted message enclosed with HTML tags in the format “&lt;HTML&gt;&lt;encrypted Response&gt; &lt;/HTML&gt;”. The RAT decrypts the response and writes them into the memory stream.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>We discovered that the C2 server sends an encrypted stream of binary to the RAT. The RAT decrypts the binary stream into a DLL file in the memory and executes its exported functions. The decrypted DLL functions as a plugin to the SpiceRAT.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5a3dc2ed-a992-424d-bb36-1308aef98731.png" class="kg-image" alt="A screen shot of a computer program

Description automatically generated" loading="lazy" width="605" height="868" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-5a3dc2ed-a992-424d-bb36-1308aef98731.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5a3dc2ed-a992-424d-bb36-1308aef98731.png 605w"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">&nbsp;Sample function of SpiceRAT executing the export functions of plugin.&nbsp;</em></i></figcaption></figure><h2 id="spicerat-plugin-enables-further-attacks">SpiceRAT plugin enables further attacks&nbsp;&nbsp;</h2><p>SpiceRAT plugin is a 32-bit dynamic link library compiled on March 28, 2023. The plugin has an original filename “Moudle.dll” and has two export functions: <code>Download</code> and <code>RunPE</code>.&nbsp;</p><p>The <code>Download</code> function of the plugin appears to access decrypted response data from the C2 server stored in the victim’s memory and writes them into a file on disk, likely as commanded by the C2.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5c61d6e1-d97b-4f97-9580-b3ec407de2c8.png" class="kg-image" alt="A screenshot of a computer program

Description automatically generated" loading="lazy" width="1015" height="887" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-5c61d6e1-d97b-4f97-9580-b3ec407de2c8.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-5c61d6e1-d97b-4f97-9580-b3ec407de2c8.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-5c61d6e1-d97b-4f97-9580-b3ec407de2c8.png 1015w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The downloader function of SpiceRAT plugin.</em></i></figcaption></figure><p>The <code>RunPE</code> function appears to execute arbitrary commands or binaries that were likely sent from C2 using the WinExec API.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-53082aa8-79cb-48f1-9c0d-5e4575ea52fb.png" class="kg-image" alt="A computer screen with text and numbers

Description automatically generated" loading="lazy" width="1600" height="876" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-53082aa8-79cb-48f1-9c0d-5e4575ea52fb.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-53082aa8-79cb-48f1-9c0d-5e4575ea52fb.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-53082aa8-79cb-48f1-9c0d-5e4575ea52fb.png 1600w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><i><em class="italic" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A sample function to run a PE file.&nbsp;</em></i></figcaption></figure><h2 id="c2-communications">C2 communications&nbsp;</h2><p><a href="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/sneakychef-sugarghost-rat/" rel="noreferrer"><u>SneakyChef’s</u></a> infrastructure includes the malware’s download and command and control (C2) servers.&nbsp;In one attack, the threat actor hosted a malicious ZIP archive on the server 45[.]144[.]31[.]57 and hardcoded the following URL in a malicious downloader executable.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><code>http://45[.]144[.]31[.]57:80/S1VRB0HpMXR79eStog35igWKVTsdbx/chromeupdate.zip</code>servers</p><p>We observed that the threat actor used IP addresses and domain names to connect to the C2 servers in different samples of SpiceRAT in this campaign. Our research uncovered various C2 URLs hardcoded in SpiceRAT samples.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><ul><li>hxxp[://]94[.]198[.]40[.]4/homepage/index.aspx&nbsp;</li><li>hxxp[://]stock[.]adobe-service[.]net/homepage/index.aspx&nbsp;</li><li>hxxp[://]app[.]turkmensk[.]org[/]homepage[/]index.aspx&nbsp;</li></ul><p>One of the C2 servers, 94[.]198[.]40[.]4, was found to be running Windows Server 2016 and hosted on the M247 network, which is frequently abused by APT groups. Passive DNS resolution data indicate that the IP address 94[.]198[.]40[.]4 resolved to the domain app[.]turkmensk[.]org and we found another SpiceRAT sample in the wild that communicated with this domain.	&nbsp;</p><p>Further analysis of the C2 server 94[.]198[.]40[.]4 uncovered a unique C2 communication pattern of SpiceRAT. The SpiceRAT initially sends the encrypted reconnaissance data to the C2 URL through the HTTP POST method. The C2 server then responds with an encrypted message embedded in the HTML tags.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-e9e6ac40-22ff-4918-a4ee-94f5629cc9ae.png" class="kg-image" alt="A screenshot of a computer

<p>Our analysis suggests that the second request that SpiceRAT sends likely contains the encrypted stream of the victim’s machine user credentials. We found that for the third request that SpiceRAT sends from the victim machine, the C2 server responds with an encrypted stream of the SpiceRAT’s plugin binary. SpiceRAT then decrypts and injects the plugin DLL reflectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-22d07e08-a877-4bcd-939a-c729323eae7d.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="596" height="389"></figure><p>Once the plugin is downloaded and implanted on the victim’s machine, SpiceRAT sends another request with the prefix “wG.” The C2 server responds with an unencrypted message “&lt;HTML&gt;D_OK&lt;HTML&gt;”, likely to get a confirmation of successful payload download.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-df5d2e69-2c97-48ba-b208-be74909d6a82.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="594" height="340"></figure><h1 id="ttps-overlap-with-other-malware-campaigns">TTPs overlap with other malware campaigns&nbsp;&nbsp;</h1><p>Talos assesses with medium confidence that the actor SneakyChef, using SpiceRAT and SugarGh0st RAT is a Chinese-speaking actor based of the language observed in the artifacts and overlapping TTPs with other malware campaigns.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>In this campaign, we saw that SpiceRAT leverages the sideloading technique, utilizing a legitimate loader alongside a malicious loader and the encrypted payload. Although sideloading is a widely adopted tactic, technique and procedure (TTP), the choice to use the Samsung helper application to sideload the malicious DLL masquerading “ssMUIDLL.dll” file is particularly notable. This method has been previously observed in the <a href="https://unit42.paloaltonetworks.com/plugx-uses-legitimate-samsung-application-for-dll-side-loading/" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>PlugX</u></a> and <a href="https://www.forescout.com/resources/apt10/" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>SPIVY RAT</u></a> campaigns.&nbsp;</p><h1 id="coverage">Coverage&nbsp;</h1><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-76680560-fd45-4ef6-8171-9ce3e7b4b94d.png" class="kg-image" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1375" height="278" srcset="https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w600/2024/06/data-src-image-76680560-fd45-4ef6-8171-9ce3e7b4b94d.png 600w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/size/w1000/2024/06/data-src-image-76680560-fd45-4ef6-8171-9ce3e7b4b94d.png 1000w, https://blog.talosintelligence.com/content/images/2024/06/data-src-image-76680560-fd45-4ef6-8171-9ce3e7b4b94d.png 1375w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/amp-for-endpoints/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Endpoint</u></a> (formerly AMP for Endpoints) is ideally suited to prevent the execution of the malware detailed in this post. Try Secure Endpoint for free <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/amp-for-endpoints/free-trial.html?utm_medium=web-referral?utm_source=cisco&amp;utm_campaign=amp-free-trial&amp;utm_term=pgm-talos-trial&amp;utm_content=amp-free-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>here.</u></a>&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/web-security-appliance/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Web Appliance</u></a> web scanning prevents access to malicious websites and detects malware used in these attacks.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/email-security/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Email</u></a> (formerly Cisco Email Security) can block malicious emails sent by threat actors as part of their campaign. You can try Secure Email for free <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/cloud-mailbox-defense?utm_medium=web-referral&amp;utm_source=cisco&amp;utm_campaign=cmd-free-trial-request&amp;utm_term=pgm-talos-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>here</u></a>.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/firewalls/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Firewall</u></a> (formerly Next-Generation Firewall and Firepower NGFW) appliances such as <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/collateral/security/firepower-ngfw-virtual/datasheet-c78-742858.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Threat Defense Virtual</u></a>, <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/adaptive-security-appliance-asa-software/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Adaptive Security Appliance</u></a> and <a href="https://meraki.cisco.com/products/appliances" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Meraki MX</u></a> can detect malicious activity associated with this threat.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/threat-grid/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Malware Analytics</u></a> (Threat Grid) identifies malicious binaries and builds protection into all Cisco Secure products.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://umbrella.cisco.com/" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Umbrella</u></a>, Cisco's secure internet gateway (SIG), blocks users from connecting to malicious domains, IPs and URLs, whether users are on or off the corporate network. Sign up for a free trial of Umbrella <a href="https://signup.umbrella.com/?utm_medium=web-referral?utm_source=cisco&amp;utm_campaign=umbrella-free-trial&amp;utm_term=pgm-talos-trial&amp;utm_content=automated-free-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>here</u></a>.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/web-security-appliance/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Secure Web Appliance</u></a> (formerly Web Security Appliance) automatically blocks potentially dangerous sites and tests suspicious sites before users access them.&nbsp;</p><p>Additional protections with context to your specific environment and threat data are available from the <a href="https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/security/firepower-management-center/index.html" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Firewall Management Center</u></a>.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://signup.duo.com/?utm_source=talos&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=duo-free-trial" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Cisco Duo</u></a> provides multi-factor authentication for users to ensure only those authorized are accessing your network.&nbsp;</p><p>Open-source Snort Subscriber Rule Set customers can stay up to date by downloading the latest rule pack available for purchase on <a href="https://www.snort.org/products" rel="noreferrer noopener"><u>Snort.org</u></a>. Snort SID for this threat is 63538.&nbsp;</p><p>ClamAV detections are also available for this threat:&nbsp;</p><p>Win.Trojan.SpiceRAT-10031450-0&nbsp;</p><p>Win.Trojan.SpiceRATPlugin-10031560-0&nbsp;</p><p>Win.Trojan.SpiceRATLauncher-10031652-0&nbsp;</p><p>Win.Trojan.SpiceRATLauncherEXE-10032013-0&nbsp;</p><h1 id="indicators-of-compromise">Indicators of Compromise&nbsp;</h1><p>Indicators of Compromise associated with this threat can be found <a href="https://github.com/Cisco-Talos/IOCs/tree/main/2024/06" rel="noreferrer">here</a>.&nbsp;</p>
